EXP: This use of 'whole' comes from Quine and I have never seen the word used this way by the layman.  The difference between a whole and a concept is that in the sentence "I belong to whole b" I cannot infer "I am a b" whereas from "I belong to concept b" I can infer that "I am a b".  In elementary school when we were put into classes we could say "I am a 4th grader".  In the lower grades we even gave the classes names like 'tiger' and we could say "I am a tiger".  So when Quine says "there are more age_wholes than grade_wholes in the white school" he is using 'whole' in the sense of 'class'.
